         <abstract>
            <p>The conventional way to improve expected return on an equity portfolio is to depart from perfect diversification -- in other words, to incur significant exposure to the risk in specific securities. Another way to improve expected return by incurring extra risk is leverage. Because the extra risk incurred by levering a perfectly diversified portfolio is market, rather than specific, risk it improves expected return even when trading skill is absent -- and transaction costs are substantially lower.</p>
